## Self-Check
1. What is the purpose of notifyListeners() in Provider?
2. What is the difference between push and pushReplacement in navigation?
3. When would you use named routes?',3,1,'2026-02-16 07:11:08'),
(36,6,'Firebase & Backend Integration','## What is Firebase?

Firebase is Google''s mobile and web application development platform. It provides backend services without writing server code.

## Firebase Services

- **Firestore**: NoSQL cloud database, real-time sync
- **Authentication**: Email/password, Google, Facebook, phone login
- **Storage**: File storage for images and videos
- **Cloud Functions**: Serverless backend logic
- **Analytics**: App usage tracking
- **Cloud Messaging (FCM)**: Push notifications

## Setting Up Firebase in Flutter

```bash
# Install FlutterFire CLI
dart pub global activate flutterfire_cli

# Configure Firebase
flutterfire configure

# Add dependencies to pubspec.yaml
firebase_core: ^2.0.0
cloud_firestore: ^4.0.0
firebase_auth: ^4.0.0
```

## Firestore CRUD

```dart
final db = FirebaseFirestore.instance;

// Create
await db.collection(''students'').add({
  ''name'': ''Amara'',
  ''email'': ''amara@example.com'',
  ''course'': ''Flutter Development'',
  ''createdAt'': FieldValue.serverTimestamp(),
});

// Read (real-time stream)
StreamBuilder<QuerySnapshot>(
  stream: db.collection(''students'').snapshots(),
  builder: (context, snapshot) {
    if (!snapshot.hasData) return CircularProgressIndicator();
    final docs = snapshot.data!.docs;
    return ListView.builder(
      itemCount: docs.length,
      itemBuilder: (context, i) => ListTile(
        title: Text(docs[i][''name'']),
      ),
    );
  },
)

// Update
await db.collection(''students'').doc(docId).update({''course'': ''Advanced Flutter''});

// Delete
await db.collection(''students'').doc(docId).delete();
```

## Firebase Authentication

```dart
final auth = FirebaseAuth.instance;

// Register
await auth.createUserWithEmailAndPassword(
  email: ''user@example.com'',
  password: ''SecurePass123'',
);

// Login
await auth.signInWithEmailAndPassword(
  email: ''user@example.com'',
  password: ''SecurePass123'',
);

// Logout
await auth.signOut();

// Check auth state
StreamBuilder<User?>(
  stream: auth.authStateChanges(),
  builder: (context, snapshot) {
    if (snapshot.hasData) return HomeScreen();
    return LoginScreen();
  },
)
```

## Practical Task

Build a note-taking app with Firebase. Features: email/password authentication, create/read/update/delete notes stored in Firestore, real-time sync across devices. Each user sees only their own notes.

## Self-Check
1. What is the difference between Firestore and Firebase Realtime Database?
2. How does authStateChanges() work?
3. What is a Firestore collection vs a document?',4,1,'2026-02-16 07:11:08'),
(37,6,'Publishing & App Store Deployment','## Preparing Your App for Release

Before publishing, your app must be production-ready: no debug code, proper icons, splash screen, and optimised performance.

## App Icons & Splash Screen

```bash
# flutter_launcher_icons package
flutter pub add flutter_launcher_icons

# pubspec.yaml
flutter_launcher_icons:
  android: true
  ios: true
  image_path: ''assets/icon.png''  # 1024x1024px

flutter pub run flutter_launcher_icons
```

## Building for Release

```bash
# Android APK
flutter build apk --release
# Output: build/app/outputs/flutter-apk/app-release.apk

# Android App Bundle (required for Play Store)
flutter build appbundle --release
# Output: build/app/outputs/bundle/release/app-release.aab

# iOS (requires Mac + Xcode)
flutter build ios --release
```

## Google Play Store Submission

1. Create Google Play Developer account ($25 one-time fee)
2. Create a new app in Play Console
3. Complete store listing: title, description, screenshots, icon
4. Set content rating
5. Set up pricing and distribution
6. Upload your .aab file
7. Submit for review (typically 1-3 days)

## App Store (iOS) Submission

1. Enrol in Apple Developer Program ($99/year)
2. Create App ID in Apple Developer portal
3. Create app in App Store Connect
4. Archive and upload from Xcode
5. Complete metadata: description, screenshots, keywords
6. Submit for review (typically 1-2 days)

## App Store Optimisation (ASO)

ASO is SEO for app stores:
- **Title**: Include primary keyword (50 chars max)
- **Description**: First 3 lines are most important
- **Keywords**: Research with Sensor Tower or AppFollow
- **Screenshots**: Show key features, use device frames
- **Ratings**: Prompt users to rate at the right moment

## Practical Task

Prepare your note-taking app for release. Add a proper app icon and splash screen. Build a release APK. Create a complete Play Store listing with description, screenshots, and content rating. (You don''t need to actually publish — just prepare all assets.)

## Self-Check
1. What is the difference between an APK and an App Bundle?
2. What is App Store Optimisation?
3. What is the annual cost of an Apple Developer account?',5,1,'2026-02-16 07:11:08'),
(38,6,'Advanced Flutter: Animations & Performance','## Flutter Animations

Animations make apps feel polished and responsive. Flutter provides several animation systems.

## Implicit Animations (Easiest)

Implicit animations automatically animate between values:

```dart
AnimatedContainer(
  duration: Duration(milliseconds: 300),
  curve: Curves.easeInOut,
  width: _isExpanded ? 200 : 100,
  height: _isExpanded ? 200 : 100,
  color: _isExpanded ? Colors.blue : Colors.red,
  child: Text(''Tap me''),
)

AnimatedOpacity(
  opacity: _isVisible ? 1.0 : 0.0,
  duration: Duration(milliseconds: 500),
  child: Text(''Fade me''),
)
```

## Explicit Animations (More Control)

```dart
class SpinningLogo extends StatefulWidget {
  @override
  _SpinningLogoState createState() => _SpinningLogoState();
}

class _SpinningLogoState extends State<SpinningLogo>
    with SingleTickerProviderStateMixin {
  late AnimationController _controller;

  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    _controller = AnimationController(
      duration: Duration(seconds: 2),
      vsync: this,
    )..repeat();
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return RotationTransition(
      turns: _controller,
      child: FlutterLogo(size: 100),
    );
  }

  @override
  void dispose() {
    _controller.dispose();
    super.dispose();
  }
}
```

## Performance Optimisation

1. Use `const` constructors wherever possible
2. Use `ListView.builder` instead of `ListView` for long lists
3. Avoid rebuilding the entire widget tree — use `Consumer` or `Selector` with Provider
4. Use `RepaintBoundary` to isolate expensive widgets
5. Profile with Flutter DevTools: identify jank (frames taking >16ms)

## Practical Task

Add animations to your note-taking app: animated list item insertion/deletion, a hero animation when opening a note, and a loading shimmer effect while data loads from Firestore.

## Self-Check
1. What is the difference between implicit and explicit animations?
2. Why should you always call dispose() on an AnimationController?
3. What is the target frame rate for smooth Flutter animations?',6,1,'2026-02-16 07:11:08'),
(39,6,'Monetisation & Analytics','## Monetising Your App

There are several business models for mobile apps:

**Free with Ads**: Show ads using Google AdMob. Low revenue per user but scales with downloads.
**Freemium**: Free basic features, paid premium features. Most popular model.
**Paid App**: One-time purchase. Works for niche, high-value apps.
**Subscription**: Recurring monthly/annual fee. Best for content and services.
**In-App Purchases**: Buy virtual goods, extra content, or features.

## Google AdMob Integration

```dart
// pubspec.yaml
google_mobile_ads: ^3.0.0

// Banner ad
final BannerAd myBanner = BannerAd(
  adUnitId: ''ca-app-pub-3940256099942544/6300978111'', // Test ID
  size: AdSize.banner,
  request: AdRequest(),
  listener: BannerAdListener(
    onAdLoaded: (ad) => setState(() => _isBannerLoaded = true),
    onAdFailedToLoad: (ad, error) => ad.dispose(),
  ),
);
myBanner.load();
```

## In-App Purchases

```dart
// in_app_purchase package
final InAppPurchase _iap = InAppPurchase.instance;

// Check availability
final bool available = await _iap.isAvailable();

// Load products
const Set<String> ids = {''premium_monthly'', ''premium_annual''};
final ProductDetailsResponse response = await _iap.queryProductDetails(ids);

// Purchase
await _iap.buyNonConsumable(
  purchaseParam: PurchaseParam(productDetails: response.productDetails.first),
);
```

## Firebase Analytics

```dart
final analytics = FirebaseAnalytics.instance;

// Log custom event
await analytics.logEvent(
  name: ''course_started'',
  parameters: {''course_id'': ''5'', ''course_name'': ''Flutter Dev''},
);

// Log screen view
await analytics.logScreenView(screenName: ''CourseDetail'');

// Set user property
await analytics.setUserProperty(name: ''subscription_tier'', value: ''premium'');
```

## Practical Task

Add a freemium model to your note-taking app: free users can create up to 5 notes, premium users have unlimited notes. Implement a paywall screen with in-app purchase. Add Firebase Analytics events for key user actions.

## Self-Check
1. What is the difference between a consumable and non-consumable in-app purchase?
2. What is the freemium model?
3. What Firebase Analytics event would you log when a user completes a purchase?',7,1,'2026-02-16 07:11:08'),
(40,6,'Capstone: Full Mobile Application','## Final Project: Build a Complete Mobile App

